    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear the deep exhaustion in your words, and that feeling of emptiness where the old you has vanished is incredibly painful. It sounds like you are standing in a vast, silent hall where the furniture has been removed, leaving only the echo of who you used to be. When the person you knew fades away, it can feel like trying to hold onto smoke, and the only thing left is the cold floor beneath your feet.\n\nBut even in that hollow space, there is a strange kind of clarity, like a goblin who has finally stopped trying to climb a mountain and decided to sit on a rock and watch the clouds. You don't have to save the person who is gone; sometimes, the only thing left to do is to let the goblin in the jar finally get out and breathe. That little goblin isn't trying to fix the movie or save the ghost; it's just trying to find a warm cup of tea in a world that feels too cold.\n\nIt's okay if the goblin stories don't make sense right now. Sometimes, when the world feels like a broken film reel, the only thing that matters is the tiny, stubborn goblin who refuses to let the screen go black. You don't need",
